An Exploratory Analysis of Loan Data from Prosper¶

by Atonye Eben-Foby¶

Introduction¶

This notebook will document my efforts to exploratory analyze data from Prosper MarketPlace, a peer to peer lending industry. This data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

This dataset has 113937 observations and 81 variables. The data set has no duplicate records.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The main features I will be focusing on in this analysis are:

  • ProsperRating(alpha): The Prosper Rating assigned at the time the listing was created between AA - HR. Applicable for loans originated after July 2009.
  • CreditGrade: The Credit rating that was assigned at the time the listing went live. Applicable for listings pre-2009 period and will only be populated for those listings.
  • IncomeRange: The income range of the borrower at the time the listing was created.
  • BorrowerAPR: The Borrower's Annual Percentage Rate (APR) for the loan.
  • EmploymentStatus: The employment status of the borrower at the time they posted the listing.
  • LoanStatus: The current status of the loan: Cancelled, Chargedoff, Completed, Current, Defaulted, FinalPaymentInProgress, PastDue. The PastDue status will be accompanied by a delinquency bucket.
  • MonthlyLoanPayment: The scheduled monthly loan payment.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

The features that will help support my investigation into the main feautures are:

  • BorrowerRate: The Borrower's interest rate for this loan.
  • StatedMonthlyIncome: The monthly income the borrower stated at the time the listing was created.
  • DebtToIncomeRatio: The debt to income ratio of the borrower at the time the credit profile was pulled. This value is Null if the debt to income ratio is not available. This value is capped at 10.01 (any debt to income ratio larger than 1000% will be returned as 1001%).
  • LP_GrossPrincipalLoss: The gross charged off amount of the loan.
  • LoanOriginalAmount: The origination amount of the loan.
  • EstimatedReturn: The estimated return assigned to the listing at the time it was created. Estimated return is the difference between the Estimated Effective Yield and the Estimated Loss Rate. Applicable for loans originated after July 2009.
  • LoanOriginationDate: The date the loan was originated.
  • Term: The length of the loan expressed in months.
  • IsBorrowerHomeowner: A Borrower will be classified as a homowner if they have a mortgage on their credit profile or provide documentation confirming they are a homeowner.

Assessing & Cleaning Data¶

The Nulls in the dataset¶

This dataset consist of a lot of null values. Most rightfully so. For some variables, they only apply to loans pre July 2009 like creditGrade, some only apply to loans post July 2009 like EstimatedEffectiveYield, EstimatedLoss, EstimatedReturn, ProsperRating (numeric), ProsperRating (Alpha), ProsperScore. Some of the variables are also not applicable to all borrowers like GroupKey, CurrentCreditLines, OpenCreditLines, FirstRecordedCreditLine, InquiriesLast6months, DebtToIncomeRatio etc.

Theres not a lot to do with the nans in this dataset because of these reasons but for columns like the BorrowerAPR that can be calculated, I will be doing so in my analysis. I will also be dropping the columns that I woud not be using for the analysis.

There are 25 null values in the BorrowerAPR column.After a google search I found out that the Annual Percentage Rate (APR) is the cost you pay each year to borrow money, including fees, expressed as a percentage. So the BorrowerAPR = BorrowerRate + fees. Since we have the BorrowerRate for these missing BorrowerAPR's, I will be estimating the APR by adding the average borrower fee to each missing APR's borrower rate.

In [10]:
#find the average borrower fee of the dataset
borrowerfee = prosperloan["BorrowerAPR"] - prosperloan["BorrowerRate"]
borrowerfee.mean()
Out[10]:
0.026041364737692252
In [11]:
#fill the null values with the summation of borrower rate and the mean borrowerfee
prosperloan["BorrowerAPR"].fillna(prosperloan["BorrowerRate"] + borrowerfee.mean(), inplace=True)
In [12]:
#check if there a null values
prosperloan['BorrowerAPR'].isnull().any()
Out[12]:
False

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

  • 21% of the Borrowers are C rated borrowers. This is the highest percentage of individuals in any of the Prosper rating categories.
  • Most borrowers earn between 25,000 and 49,999 dollars.
  • The BorrowerAPR and BorrowerRate have very similar distribution. This is due to the fact that APR =Rate+Fees
  • Only 0.7% of borrowers are unemployed. Another 0.7% are retired and the rest of the loans are taken by individuals employed in some capacity
  • The Monthly loan payment is a leptokurtik right skewed with an extreme peak at 100-200 dollars. The histogram for stated monthly income showed only one bin because of the extreme values in the dataset. I limited the plot to show a little over the 75th percentile.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

  • From the analysis of the data we can see that ProsperRating(alpha) that is only applicable to loans post July 2009 is very similar to the CreditGrade used for pre 2009 loans. So I replaced the NC (no credit) credit grade with HR (high risk) credit grade and merged these columns.
  • I also calculated the 25 missing BorrowerAPR values by adding the mean loan fees to their borrower rate.
  • The histogram showing the distribution of the stated monthly income had such a wide spread of values. Because of the extreme value like the maximum value being 1,750,000,000 and the median being about 5600, I limited the bins to only show the spread of values for values in the range minimum stated monthly income to a little above the 75th percentile so I could capture as much off the distribution in my visualization and get rid of the outliers.
  • I also replaced all not employed income range category with 0 dollars because unemployed people aren't making any money and there was already a $\0 category in the dataset.

Conclusion¶

Most borrowers earn between 25,000 and 49,999 dollars. The highest percentage(21%) of the dataset belong to the C Prosper Rating category. 98% of borrowers in the dataset are employed in some capacity, proving that most loans are given to people that have the capacity as at the time of loan application to pay back.
Very few low income earners fall into high prosper rating categories (AA, A and B). The average loss on defaulted loans is only slightly higher than the average loss on charged off loans. As the loan original amount increases so does the monthly loan payment. The defaulted loans are very few for AA category and increase as the ratings go towards the HR category. The average BorrowerAPR is at it's lowest in 2005 and highest in 2011. There was a steady decline in average estimated return from 2011-2014. The 12 month termed loans typically do not exceed 10000 dollars. The loan original amount is affected by the prosper rating as HR rated borrowers typically take out less loans than AA rated borrowers. The lower prosper rating categories have a higher estimated return than the higher prosper rating categories. Homeowners have a lower APR than non home owners.

Limitations¶

  • There were values in the IncomeRange column categorized as Not Displayed. I tried to input these IncomeRange by iterating through the rows of the data set and multiplying their StatedMonthlyIncome value by 12 to find out the exact income ranges they belonged to. I discovered that it was taking a really long time to iterate through the rows so I just had to drop the rows instead.
  • Dataset had too many variables so it was hard to pick what variables to focus on for the analysis
  • It took some time to get used to the meaning of the variables since I have no background in finance.
